title: The <span style="color: #E3000F;">Social Democrats</span> reunify!
subtitle: The <span style="color: #D47B9B;">**USPD**</span> merged into the <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span>
tags: event
view-if: year = 1922 and month = 9
max-visits: 1

From the onset of WW1 and the <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span>’s subsequent splitting due to conflicts between the pacifist Independents and the ‘social patriotic’ party leadership, the <span style="color: #D47B9B;">**USPD**</span> and <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span> have often clashed. Many times has the <span style="color: #D47B9B;">**USPD**</span> accused the <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span> of being traitors to the cause of a proper Republic without the tethers of the old guard, ever since the <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span>’s role in the November Revolution was mired with compromise towards the reactionary remnants. However, the tides have begun to shift; the <span style="color: #D47B9B;">**USPD**</span>’s policy of rejecting bourgeois cooperation has become more of a liability, with the <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span>’s attempted efforts in stabilizing the Republic legitimizing their position. Additionally, the original reason for the <span style="color: #D47B9B;">**USPD**</span>’s split — the <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span>’s support for participation in WW1 — has largely been overshadowed by their common interests in negotiating with the Entente nations to lower reparations along with the threat brought by the assassination of Walther Rathenau, a prominent Jewish industrialist known for presiding over the Treaty of Rapallo. Thus, after months of negotiations between the two parties, the <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span> has finally reunified. 

