With most of the delegates from the <span style="color: #D47B9B;">**USPD**</span> and their affiliated labour unions accepting the final decision of the <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span>, the merger goes through smoothly. Arthur Crispien and Hermann Müller, along with various leaders from both parties attend the unification congress, marking the end of the <span style="color: #D47B9B;">**USPD**</span> as a major competitor to the <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span>’s influence over the working class. The few who don’t join, belonging to an internal clique of Moscow-sympathetic Independents, leave to join the <span style="color: #8B0000;">**KPD**</span>, and a tiny minority opt to remain in the <span style="color: #D47B9B;">**USPD**</span>, essentially presiding over the party’s rotting corpse.

